/*!
    \page strules-manual.html
    \title ST Specific Rules
    \startpage {strules-manual.html}{ST Specific Rules}
    \nextpage Predefined Rules    

    
    \section1 Overview
    
    ST specific rules override \l {qmake Features} {QS features} by defining additional rules common 
    to development projects of ST division. Two set of rules, implemented in qmake project include 
    files (\c {.pri}), are available in the \tt {$${\l {QSMAKEPATH}}/rules} directory:
    
    \list
        \li standard project rules (\c {standard_project.pri} file), which define variables and 
            compiler rules specific to any ST development project.
        \li LDTools project rules (\c {ldtools_project.pri} file), based on standard project rules, 
            which define additional features specific to project files generated with LDTools.
    \endlist
    
    
    \section1 Prerequisites
    
    \list
        \li QS qmake features must be installed. See \l {Installation} {features installation} 
            section for more details.
        \li Any project source tree must contain only one qmake project file (\c {.pro}).
        \li qmake project file has to include the desired ST specific rules file, at least after 
            target-specific variables definition. Prefers use \l {QSMAKEPATH} variable to retrieve 
            the rules file location.
    \endlist
                                    
    For example, for a project including standard project rules:
    
    \snippet doc_src_strules-manual.pro  standard rules
    
    
    \section1 Table of Contents
    
    \list
        \li \l {Predefined Rules}
        \li \l {Metadata Generation}
        \li \l {Pseudo Variables}
        \li \l {Examples}
    \endlist        
*/


/*!
    \page strules-predefined-rules.html
    \title Predefined Rules
    \previouspage ST Specific Rules
    \nextpage Metadata Generation
    
    
    \section1 Default Qt Configurations
    
    ST specific rules overrides default \l [qsfeatures] {Predefined Rules} {Qt configurations 
    predefined in QS features}. Below a description of CONFIG values updated:
     
    \table
    \header
        \li {2, 1} Option
        \li Description
    \header
        \li {3, 1} Build Modes
    \row
        \li \c {+}
        \li \c {debug_and_release}
        \li Project built in both debug and release modes, regardless of platorm and build 
            environment (except for auxiliary target).
    \row
        \li \c {+}
        \li \c {build_all}
        \li Enables project built in both debug and release modes by default.
    \row
        \li {3, 1}
    \header
        \li {3, 1} Compiler Options    
    \row
        \li \c {+}
        \li \c {precompile_header}
        \li Enables precompiled headers support.
    \endtable
    
    
    \section1 Additional Features
    
    ST specific rules also provides following CONFIG additional features:
    
    \table
    \header
        \li Option
        \li Description
    \row
        \li \c {ldtools}
        \li \e {LDTools rules only:} enables LDTools-styled project by:
            \list
                \li assigning the value of \c {DESTDIR} to \tt 
                    {$${\l {INSTALLDIR}}/${\l {BUILD_MKSPEC}}/${\l {LIBRARY_MODE}}/${\l {BUILD_MODE}}}.
                \li ignoring \c {INSTALLS} variable definitions (installation handled by LDTArtifact 
                    tool).
                \li processing below LDTools custom file rules:
                \list
                     \li optional package user rules \tt {${\l {PACKAGE}}/common.pri}.
                     \li optional manual sources definition \c {$${_PRO_FILE_PWD_}/_sources.pri}.
                     \li optional project extra rules \c {$${_PRO_FILE_PWD_}/_custom.pri}.
                \endlist
                \li adding LDTArtifact deployment tool as target post-link command.
            \endlist
    \endtable
    
    
    \section1 Projects Package
    
    A package represents a set of related projects delivered together. Each package directory 
    has to include an installation directory (i.e. a \c {Delivery} folder), and an optional source 
    code directory containing all projects to build. Note that most of the time, a package will be 
    equivalent to a Subversion repository.
    
    Any project including ST specific rules must be defined inside a package to be processed by 
    qmake tool.
    
    
    \section1 Project Building

    \section3 Target Definition
    
    By default, binary target names are automatically suffixed by the \l [qsfeatures] {Target 
    Definition} {debug modifier} \c {[d]}, if none is already applied. However, if target should 
    have the same name in debug and release modes, suffixes it by the \c {[]} modifier in order to 
    deactivate this mechanism.
    
    Furthermore, ST specific rules initialize target \l {PROPERTIES} members as follows:
    
    \table
    \header
        \li Member
        \li Value
        \li Notes
    \row
        \li \c {version}
        \li \c {$$(VERSION).$$(BUILDNUMBER)}
        \li {1, 2} Jenkins variables \c {$$(NAME)}, \c {$$(VERSION)} and \c {$$(BUILDNUMBER)} are 
            available when project is rebuilt via a Jenkins job.
    \row
        \li \c {product}
        \li \c {$$(NAME)}
    \row
        \li {3, 1} 
    \row
        \li \c {company}
        \li \c {Diginext}
        \li
    \row
        \li \c {domain}
        \li \c {diginext.fr}
        \li
    \row
        \li \c {copyright}
        \li \c {Copyright (C) %y %c}
        \li Will give when resolved: \c {Copyright (C) <year> Diginext}.
    \endtable   
        
    \section3 Installation Definition

    Installation directory, defined by \l {INSTALLDIR} variable, must point to \c {Delivery} 
    directory of current package or one of its subdirectories. If not specified in your project file, 
    this variable will be assigned to \tt {${\l {PACKAGE}}/Delivery} by default.
    
    Moreover, \c {target.path} variable, defined in \c {INSTALLS} variables set, will be 
    automatically assigned to \tt {${\l {BUILD_MKSPEC}}/${\l {LIBRARY_MODE}}/${\l {BUILD_MODE}}} if 
    not specified.
    
    \section3 Compiler Options
    
    Binary target only. ST specific rules enhances \l [qsfeatures] {Compiler Options} {compiler and 
    linker options defined in QS features}. Below table lists additional compilation rules 
    implemented:
    
    \table
    \header
        \li Scope
        \li Value
        \li Description
    \header
        \li {3, 1} Preprocessor Macros
    \row
        \li 
        \li \tt {$$\l {TARGET([mode])}{TARGET()}_LIB}
        \li \e {Shared library target only:} defines symbols import/export control macro.
    \row
        \li \span {class=nowrap} {Windows based}
        \li \c {_WINDOWS} \br
            \c {_WIN32_PLATEFORM_}
        \li Additional Windows 32/64 bits platform preprocessor macros.
    \row
        \li Linux based
        \li \c {_LINUX_PLATEFORM_}
        \li Additional Linux platform preprocessor macro.
    \row
        \li {3, 1}
    \header
        \li {3, 1} C/C++ Compiler Options       
    \row
        \li Visual C++
        \li \span {class=nowrap} {\c {-Zc:strictStrings:none}}
        \li \e {\c {release} mode only}: enables string literal type conversion.
    \endtable
*/


